    "elements": [
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1999_Solutions_1999s_page_002_14",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Second solution: It will be a bit more convenient to assume P(0) = 1 (which we may achieve by rescaling unless P(0) = 0, in which case there is nothing to prove) and to prove that there exists D > 0 such that S-, IP(x)|dx > D, or even such that fo |P(x)| dx ≥ D.",
        "bbox": [
          0.12593985717039372,
          0.6641865077302177,
          0.49076965993777677,
          0.7398313490103283
        ],
        "order": 27
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1999_Solutions_1999s_page_002_15",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "We first reduce to the case where P has all of its roots in (0, 1}. If this is not the case, we can factor P(x) as Q(x)R(x), where @ has all roots in the interval and R has none. Then R is either always positive or always negative on (0, 1]; assume the former. Let k be the largest positive real number such that R(x) - kx ≥ 0 on [0, 1]; then",
        "bbox": [
          0.12593986385585723,
          0.7427325581692049,
          0.4906015092597036,
          0.8401162787665676
        ],
        "order": 28
      }
    ]
  },
